        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Construction project management has its own vocabulary — a mix of legal terms, accounting concepts, and field management jargon that can be confusing for contractors new to software or new to the industry. This glossary covers the most important terms you'll encounter when evaluating construction management software or working on commercial projects.</p>

        <h2>A</h2>

        <h3>AIA Billing</h3>
        <p>A billing format standardized by the American Institute of Architects (AIA) for construction projects. Typically uses G702 (Application for Payment) and G703 (Schedule of Values) forms. Required by many GCs and owners on commercial projects. Subcontractors submit monthly pay applications using these forms showing work completed to date.</p>

        <h3>Application for Payment (Pay App)</h3>
        <p>A formal request from a contractor or subcontractor to be paid for work completed during a billing period. Commercial pay apps typically follow AIA format and include a Schedule of Values breakdown showing percentage complete for each line item.</p>

        <h3>As-Built Drawings</h3>
        <p>Revised construction drawings showing how a project was actually built, including any changes from the original design. Contractors are typically required to maintain and deliver as-built drawings at project completion. Field management software like Fieldwire facilitates as-built markup directly on digital drawings.</p>

        <h2>B</h2>

        <h3>Bid Bond</h3>
        <p>A type of surety bond submitted with a bid that guarantees the bidder will enter into the contract if awarded. If the bidder wins but refuses to sign, the bond compensates the owner for the difference between the winning bid and the next-lowest bid.</p>

        <h3>Budget vs. Actual</h3>
        <p>A comparison of what was estimated (budget) versus what was actually spent (actual costs) on a job or budget line item. Real-time budget vs. actual tracking is one of the most valuable features in construction project management software.</p>

        <h2>C</h2>

        <h3>Certificate of Insurance (COI)</h3>
        <p>A document from an insurance company confirming that a contractor or subcontractor has active insurance coverage, including general liability and workers' compensation. GCs typically require current COIs from all subcontractors before allowing them to work. Software like Sage 100 Contractor and Foundation automate COI expiration tracking.</p>

        <h3>Change Order</h3>
        <p>A formal document authorizing a modification to the original scope of work, price, or schedule of a construction contract. All parties (owner, GC, contractor) must sign a change order for it to be binding. Construction software tracks change orders through their approval workflow and adjusts project budgets accordingly.</p>

        <h3>Closeout</h3>
        <p>The final phase of a construction project, including final inspections, punch list completion, as-built drawing delivery, O&amp;M manual submission, lien waiver collection, and final payment processing.</p>

        <h3>Committed Cost</h3>
        <p>Costs that have been approved and obligated through a purchase order, subcontract, or similar commitment — but not yet billed or paid. Tracking committed costs alongside actual costs gives a more complete picture of a project's financial status. Sophisticated PM software distinguishes between estimated, committed, actual, and projected costs.</p>

        <h3>Cost Code</h3>
        <p>A numerical or alphanumeric code used to categorize costs within a project. For example: 03.100 might represent concrete formwork, while 05.200 represents structural steel. Cost codes allow contractors to track spending by work category and compare actual costs against estimates by category. The Construction Specifications Institute (CSI) MasterFormat is the most widely used cost code standard.</p>

        <h3>Cost-Plus Contract</h3>
        <p>A contract structure where the owner pays the contractor's actual costs plus a fee (fixed or percentage). Creates less financial risk for the contractor but requires transparent cost documentation. Software with strong cost tracking is especially important for cost-plus work.</p>

        <h2>D</h2>

        <h3>Davis-Bacon Act</h3>
        <p>A federal law requiring contractors on federally funded construction projects over $2,000 to pay prevailing wages as determined by the Department of Labor. Davis-Bacon compliance requires certified payroll reporting. Construction-specific accounting software like Foundation and Sage 100 Contractor handles Davis-Bacon payroll natively.</p>

        <h3>Daily Report (Daily Log)</h3>
        <p>A field document recording work performed, labor on site, weather conditions, equipment used, and any notable events or issues for a given day. Daily reports are important for tracking project progress and create a legal record of site conditions. Raken is purpose-built for daily report creation; most full PM platforms include basic daily log functionality.</p>

        <h2>G</h2>

        <h3>G702 / G703</h3>
        <p>Standard AIA forms for construction billing. G702 is the Application and Certificate for Payment (the summary page). G703 is the Continuation Sheet (the Schedule of Values breakdown). These forms are required by most commercial GCs and owners. Platforms like Knowify generate G702/G703 documents automatically from project data.</p>

        <h3>Gantt Chart</h3>
        <p>A horizontal bar chart showing project tasks over time, with each bar representing the duration of a task. Gantt charts are the standard format for construction schedules. Most construction PM platforms include Gantt chart scheduling views.</p>

        <h3>General Conditions</h3>
        <p>Costs of managing a construction project that are not tied to specific work items — superintendent salary, temporary facilities, site utilities, equipment, permits, and insurance. General conditions are typically carried as a separate line item in a budget.</p>

        <h2>J</h2>

        <h3>Job Costing</h3>
        <p>The process of tracking and allocating all costs associated with a specific job — labor, materials, subcontractors, equipment, and overhead — and comparing them against the original estimate or budget. Accurate job costing is how contractors know whether they're making or losing money on each project.</p>

        <h2>L</h2>

        <h3>Lien</h3>
        <p>A legal claim against a property filed by a contractor, subcontractor, or supplier who has not been paid for work or materials. A mechanic's lien can prevent the property owner from selling or refinancing until the claim is resolved. Lien laws vary significantly by state.</p>

        <h3>Lien Waiver</h3>
        <p>A document in which a contractor or supplier waives their right to file a lien against a property, typically in exchange for receiving payment. Conditional waivers take effect when payment clears; unconditional waivers are effective immediately. GCs typically collect lien waivers from all subs and suppliers at each payment milestone.</p>

        <h2>O</h2>

        <h3>Owner's Representative</h3>
        <p>A person or firm hired by a property owner to manage the construction project on their behalf — reviewing pay applications, approving change orders, coordinating with the architect, and ensuring the owner's interests are protected. Construction software often includes owner portals that allow owner representatives to access project data.</p>

        <h2>P</h2>

        <h3>Pay Application</h3>
        <p>See Application for Payment.</p>

        <h3>Punchlist (Punch List)</h3>
        <p>A list of work items that are incomplete, incorrect, or need to be corrected before final payment is released. Punch lists are created during a walk-through near project completion. Field management tools like Fieldwire are particularly good for punch list creation and tracking linked to specific plan locations.</p>

        <h3>Purchase Order (PO)</h3>
        <p>A formal document issued by a buyer to a supplier or subcontractor specifying the goods or services to be provided, quantity, price, and delivery terms. POs create a committed cost entry in job costing and serve as the basis for billing and payment. Most construction PM platforms include purchase order management.</p>

        <h2>R</h2>

        <h3>RFI (Request for Information)</h3>
        <p>A formal document submitted by a contractor to the designer (architect, engineer) requesting clarification on a design detail, specification, or drawing. RFIs are numbered, tracked, and require a written response. Delays in RFI responses can create schedule impacts. Construction PM platforms track RFIs through their submission, review, and response lifecycle.</p>

        <h3>Retainage (Retention)</h3>
        <p>A percentage (typically 5–10%) of each progress payment withheld by the owner or GC and held until project completion. Retainage provides the owner with leverage to ensure the contractor completes all punch list items. Retainage tracking in billing software is important for accurate cash flow management.</p>

        <h2>S</h2>

        <h3>Schedule of Values (SOV)</h3>
        <p>A breakdown of a contract price into individual line items showing the value assigned to each portion of the work. The SOV is the basis for calculating monthly progress billings. For AIA billing, the SOV appears on the G703 form.</p>

        <h3>Submittal</h3>
        <p>Shop drawings, product data, samples, or other information submitted by the contractor to the architect or engineer for review and approval before installation. Submittals verify that what will be installed matches the design intent. Construction PM platforms track submittals through their creation, submission, review, and approval workflow.</p>

        <h3>Substantial Completion</h3>
        <p>The point at which a construction project is sufficiently complete for the owner to occupy and use it for its intended purpose, even if minor punch list items remain. Substantial completion typically triggers the final payment period and starts the warranty clock.</p>

        <h2>T</h2>

        <h3>Timecard</h3>
        <p>A record of hours worked by an employee, typically including date, project, cost code, and hours. Construction timecards often include multiple cost codes within a single pay period (e.g., 4 hours on job 100 / carpentry, 4 hours on job 101 / cleanup). Mobile time tracking in construction software captures this data in the field rather than at week-end from memory.</p>

        <h2>W</h2>

        <h3>WIP (Work in Progress)</h3>
        <p>An accounting concept representing the value of construction work performed but not yet billed. WIP schedules track overbilling (where billed amounts exceed costs incurred) and underbilling (where costs incurred exceed amounts billed). Accurate WIP reporting is required for percentage-of-completion revenue recognition and for bonding companies.</p>

        <h3>Workers' Compensation</h3>
        <p>Insurance that provides wage replacement and medical benefits to employees injured on the job. In construction, workers' comp costs are tracked by job and trade classification, and rates vary significantly by trade (roofers pay more than office staff). Proper workers' comp allocation is a key function of construction payroll software.</p>

